    <h2 id="etsy-requirement">Does Etsy Require Sellers to Have a Privacy Policy</h2>

    <p>Yes. Etsy's Seller Policy states that sellers who collect, use, or process personal information from buyers must provide a privacy policy that discloses those practices. While Etsy handles much of the transaction infrastructure (payment processing through Etsy Payments, messaging through the Etsy platform, and order management through the seller dashboard), sellers are still responsible for how they handle the buyer data Etsy shares with them to fulfill orders.</p>

    <p>When a buyer places an order, Etsy provides the seller with the buyer's name, shipping address, email address (in some cases), and order details. That transfer of personal data makes the seller a data controller under laws like the GDPR. Etsy acts as a platform and processes payments on your behalf, but the moment buyer data reaches your end for fulfillment, shipping label creation, customer communication, or marketing, you are responsible for disclosing how you handle it.</p>

    <p>Etsy does not generate or host a privacy policy for sellers. Unlike some e-commerce platforms that offer a built-in privacy policy template, Etsy expects sellers to create and manage their own. The platform provides a designated section in your shop's policies where you can paste a privacy policy, but the content is entirely your responsibility.</p>

    <h2 id="why-needed">Why Etsy Shop Owners Need a Privacy Policy</h2>

    <p>Beyond Etsy's own seller requirements, three forces make a privacy policy effectively mandatory for every Etsy shop, regardless of size.</p>

    <p><strong>Privacy laws apply based on where your buyers are located.</strong> If a buyer in France orders a handmade item from your shop, the GDPR applies to that transaction. A buyer from California triggers the CCPA. Canadian buyers bring PIPEDA into scope, and Brazilian buyers are covered by the LGPD. Each of these laws requires you to publish a clear privacy policy explaining what personal data you collect and why. Since Etsy shops are accessible worldwide, most sellers are subject to multiple privacy regulations simultaneously. GDPR fines for transparency failures have reached tens of millions of euros, and CCPA enforcement has targeted businesses of all sizes, including sole proprietors.</p>

    <p><strong>Third-party services you use outside Etsy require disclosure.</strong> Many Etsy sellers use tools and services beyond what Etsy provides. If you use Google Analytics to track shop traffic, ship through USPS, UPS, or FedEx using a service like ShipStation or Pirate Ship, send marketing emails through Mailchimp or Klaviyo, use bookkeeping tools like QuickBooks or Wave, or run advertising through Facebook, Google, or Pinterest, each of those services processes buyer data. Your privacy policy must disclose which third-party services receive personal information and explain what data they handle.</p>

    <p><strong>Buyers expect transparency before purchasing.</strong> A visible privacy policy signals that you take data handling seriously. For buyers entering payment information or sharing their home address with a seller they have never purchased from before, a privacy policy provides reassurance. Shops without one risk losing sales to competitors who clearly communicate their data practices, especially for higher-value items where buyer trust matters most.</p>

    <h2 id="what-to-include">What to Include in an Etsy Shop Privacy Policy</h2>

    <p>An Etsy shop's privacy policy needs to cover the specific data flows that occur when someone buys from your store. For a broader walkthrough of structuring each section, read our <a href="/resources/how-to-write-privacy-policy-for-app/">guide to writing a privacy policy</a>.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Types of personal data collected.</strong> Etsy shares buyer names, shipping addresses, and order details with sellers for fulfillment. If you communicate with buyers through Etsy Messages, you may also receive additional personal information they share voluntarily. If you collect email addresses for a mailing list or use Google Analytics on your shop, disclose those separately. List every category of data you receive or collect, whether from Etsy, from direct communication, or through third-party tools.</li>
      <li><strong>Payment processing.</strong> Etsy handles payment processing through Etsy Payments. Sellers do not directly receive credit card numbers or bank account details from buyers. Your privacy policy should explain this distinction: Etsy processes payments on your behalf, and you receive only the information necessary to fulfill the order. If you accept direct checkout or PayPal for any reason, disclose that as well.</li>
      <li><strong>How you use buyer data.</strong> Tie each data type to a specific purpose. You use shipping addresses to send orders. You use buyer names and email addresses to communicate about order status. If you use buyer data for marketing, clearly state that and explain how buyers can opt out. Vague language like "to improve your experience" does not satisfy the GDPR's transparency requirements.</li>
      <li><strong>Third-party services.</strong> Name every external service that receives buyer data. Common examples for Etsy sellers include shipping carriers (USPS, UPS, FedEx, Royal Mail), shipping management tools (ShipStation, Pirate Ship, Shippo), email marketing platforms (Mailchimp, Klaviyo), analytics (Google Analytics), advertising platforms (Facebook Ads, Pinterest Ads, Google Ads), and bookkeeping tools (QuickBooks, Wave, TaxJar). Each must be disclosed.</li>
      <li><strong>Cookies and tracking.</strong> Etsy itself sets cookies for session management and platform functionality. If you have enabled Google Analytics through Etsy's integration or run advertising pixels through third-party tools, those set additional tracking cookies. Your policy should explain which cookie categories apply (essential, analytics, marketing) and how buyers can manage preferences through browser settings.</li>
      <li><strong>Buyer rights under applicable laws.</strong> Under the GDPR, buyers can access, correct, delete, and port their data, restrict processing, and withdraw consent. Under the CCPA, California residents can request disclosure of collected data, request deletion, and opt out of the sale of personal information. Note that for data Etsy holds directly, buyers should contact Etsy. For data you hold as a seller, you are responsible for responding to these requests.</li>
      <li><strong>Data retention.</strong> State how long you keep buyer data. Order records are typically retained for tax and accounting compliance (often five to seven years depending on jurisdiction). Marketing email lists are kept until the subscriber unsubscribes. Be specific rather than stating "as long as necessary."</li>
      <li><strong>Contact information.</strong> Provide an email address where buyers can reach you with privacy questions. If you sell to EU buyers, you may need to designate a data controller and provide their contact details.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="how-to-add">How to Add a Privacy Policy to Your Etsy Shop</h2>

    <p>Once you have your privacy policy text ready, adding it to your Etsy shop takes just a few minutes. Etsy provides a dedicated section for shop policies that buyers can access from your shop page.</p>

    <ol class="steps-list">
      <li><strong>Sign in to Etsy and open your Shop Manager.</strong> Go to etsy.com, sign in to your seller account, and click the Shop Manager icon to access your dashboard.</li>
      <li><strong>Navigate to your shop settings.</strong> In the left sidebar of Shop Manager, click Settings, then click the Info & Appearance tab (or the equivalent Policies section depending on your region).</li>
      <li><strong>Find the Privacy Policy section.</strong> Scroll down to the shop policies area. Etsy provides separate fields for your privacy policy, return policy, shipping policy, and other shop policies. Click into the Privacy Policy field.</li>
      <li><strong>Paste your privacy policy text.</strong> If there is existing placeholder text, select all and replace it with your full privacy policy. Etsy's policies editor supports basic formatting, so you can structure the text with headings and paragraphs.</li>
      <li><strong>Save your changes.</strong> Click Save at the bottom of the page. Your privacy policy will now be visible to buyers who visit your shop and click on the Policies tab or link.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Some sellers also add a brief mention of their privacy policy in their shop announcement or in the "About" section, with a note directing buyers to the Policies tab for the full document. If you collect email addresses through an external form or newsletter signup outside of Etsy, include a link to your privacy policy near the signup form to meet GDPR transparency requirements at the point of data collection.</p>

    <h2 id="generator">Using BuildPrivacyPolicy's Generator for Etsy Sellers</h2>

    <p>Writing a privacy policy from scratch requires cross-referencing GDPR articles, CCPA disclosure requirements, Etsy's seller obligations, and the data practices of every third-party tool you use. That is a lot of legal surface area for a shop owner focused on making and selling products.</p>

    <p>A generator compresses that work into a guided form. You can <a href="https://buildprivacypolicy.com/">generate a privacy policy tailored to your Etsy shop</a> by answering questions that cover:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Your shop name and a contact email for privacy inquiries</li>
      <li>Which platform your shop runs on (select Web App / PWA for an Etsy shop selling through the web)</li>
      <li>The specific data types your shop collects or receives: buyer names, email addresses, shipping addresses, order details, and any additional information from direct communication</li>
      <li>Which third-party services your shop uses: Google Analytics, shipping carriers, email marketing platforms, advertising tools, and bookkeeping software</li>
      <li>How long you retain data and what security measures you follow</li>
      <li>Where your buyers are located, which determines whether the GDPR, CCPA, PIPEDA, LGPD, or other regulations apply</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The generator produces a privacy policy you can host for free on BuildPrivacyPolicy's servers, download as HTML to paste into Etsy's policies section, or copy as plain text. No signup, no account, no payment. The process takes a few minutes from start to finished policy.</p>

    <p>The output covers each required disclosure section across the GDPR, CCPA, COPPA, PIPEDA, and other major regulations. Unlike generic templates found online, the generated policy reflects the specific services, data types, and legal jurisdictions you selected. It is not a substitute for a lawyer's review if your shop handles sensitive data or sells children's products, but for the majority of Etsy sellers running standard handmade, vintage, or craft supply shops, it produces a document that is specific to your setup and far more accurate than copying a generic template.</p>

    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Does Etsy provide a privacy policy for sellers?</h3>
        <p>No. Etsy does not generate or provide a privacy policy template for sellers. Etsy has its own platform-level privacy policy that covers how Etsy collects and processes data, but individual sellers are responsible for creating and maintaining their own privacy policy that describes how they handle buyer data received through the platform.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do I need a privacy policy for my Etsy shop?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Etsy's Seller Policy requires sellers who collect or process personal information to have a privacy policy. Beyond Etsy's own requirement, privacy laws like the GDPR and CCPA require any business that collects personal data to publish a privacy policy. Since every Etsy seller receives buyer names, shipping addresses, and order details to fulfill orders, a privacy policy is effectively required for all sellers.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What privacy laws apply to Etsy sellers?</h3>
        <p>The applicable laws depend on where your buyers are located, not where your shop is based. EU buyers trigger the GDPR. California buyers trigger the CCPA. Canadian buyers bring PIPEDA into scope, and Brazilian buyers are covered by the LGPD. Since Etsy shops are accessible worldwide, most sellers are subject to multiple privacy regulations at the same time.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Where do I put my privacy policy on Etsy?</h3>
        <p>In your Shop Manager, go to Settings and find the Policies section. Etsy provides a dedicated Privacy Policy field where you can paste your policy text. Once saved, it appears on your shop page under the Policies tab where buyers can review it before purchasing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Does Etsy handle payment data for sellers?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Etsy processes payments through Etsy Payments, so sellers do not directly receive credit card numbers or bank details from buyers. Your privacy policy should explain that Etsy handles payment processing on your behalf and that you only receive the information necessary for order fulfillment, such as the buyer's name, shipping address, and order details.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is a privacy policy generator free?</h3>
        <p>Some generators are free, others charge a subscription. BuildPrivacyPolicy is completely free with no signup, no payment, and no word limits. You can generate a policy, host it at no cost, and download or copy the text to paste into your Etsy shop's policies section.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

